About 1,000 evacuated through ‘humanitarian corridor’ from Zaporizhizhia nuclear power plant
Return to menu
By Loveday Morris and Wojciech Grzedzinski 10:30 p.m.
Link copied
Link

ZAPORIZHZHIA, Ukraine — Hundreds of families trapped for days in the area around a nuclear power plant in southeastern Ukraine were evacuated Wednesday night, after Russia agreed to allow civilians to leave through “humanitarian corridors.”

They took buses to Zaporizhzhia, a 75-mile drive from the nuclear power plant that was attacked and seized by Russian forces a week ago. But Zaporizhzhia Gov. Oleksandr Starukh said the corridor between there and the besieged port city of Mariupol remains “incredibly difficult.”

Valentyna Oskolkova, 24, cradled her 5-month-old girl as she waited to get off the bus and have her information recorded before being ferried to an overnight shelter. Residents described how they had watched in horror as the battle raged at the nuclear power station.

“We understood that if it explodes, nothing will survive,” she said.

The situation had been “extremely hard,” she said. “There were no products in the stores, we didn’t have any food or medicine and people were scared to go outside.”

Oskolkova made it out with her 4-year-old son and her husband, but she said it had taken a battle to get her husband onto the bus. She had argued that she couldn’t handle the children on her own.

Others were forced to leave their partners behind, with limited space on buses. The convoy of buses and cars was held up for four hours in Vasilivka, according to Ukrainian officials.
