Most Ukrainian men are banned from leaving. Some have left anyway.
Return to menu
By Chico Harlan 9:30 p.m.
Link copied
Link

CHISINAU, Moldova — The historic stream of refugees from Ukraine — 2 million people in two weeks — is mostly composed of women and children, who have been forced to separate from husbands and fathers, in one of the most excruciating aspects of this war. Most Ukrainian men ages 18 to 60 have been barred from leaving the country, in anticipation that they may be called to fight. Their president has stayed, eliciting international recognition as a “hero.”

But the martial law aimed at bolstering the resistance is not absolute. There are exemptions — fathers with three or more children can leave, as can people with medical problems. There are also ways to sneak out: bribes to border guards, furtive dashes through unattended parts of the border. What’s clear, among the men who escaped, is that their decisions have had the capacity both to save them and shatter them.

In interviews across Moldova, 10 Ukrainian men described making it here through all sorts of means. One 38-year-old said he fled Odessa with his family in the first hours of Russia’s invasion, making it out of the country before Ukraine imposed martial law — only to later feel so ashamed that he began volunteering to help subsequent refugees. Others said their ability to make it out perhaps had depended on nothing more than the person manning the Ukrainian exit booth.
