Prosecutor general floats special tribunal to investigate allegations of Russian war crimes
Return to menu
By Lateshia Beachum 8:30 p.m.
Link copied
Link

Ukraine’s prosecutor general says an ad hoc tribunal is needed to hold individuals responsible for Russian military aggression in Ukraine.

Iryna Venediktova said at a news conference Wednesday that Russia is destroying the lives of Ukrainian citizens, and their cities and schools.

“Russian bombs are being fired into hospitals and into schools, killing our children,” she said. “These are war crimes and crimes against humanity that have been committed on our land by the invaders, and all involved in the commission of these crimes should be and shall be held responsible.”

As of Wednesday, Ukrainian courts had issued more than 40 orders against Russian politicians, authorities and supporters of the invasion, marking them as suspicious individuals connected to the war. Ukrainian courts are taking steps to declare these individuals “internationally wanted,” according to Venediktova.

Ukraine has pleaded with The Hague-based International Criminal Court to make Russia end its encroachment on its land. Russia this week snubbed International Court of Justice hearings and left empty seats in the Great Hall of Justice, the Associated Press reported.

More than nine countries have appealed to the ICC, which investigates alleged crimes against humanity, genocide, war crimes and crimes of aggression, to bring “top-level criminals” to justice for attacks on Ukrainians, according to Venediktova.

Ukraine and Russia are not among the 123 member nations of the ICC because they didn’t ratify the 1998 treaty that established the court, but Ukraine has accepted the ICC’s jurisdiction over alleged crimes in the country since 2014 .

War crimes are difficult to prosecute, and the ICC has issued five convictions for war crimes, crimes against humanity and genocide from 38 defendants, Reuters reported.

“We don’t rule out the creation of an additional international mechanism to investigate a crime of aggression,” Venediktova said.

Estonia, Germany, Latvia and Poland have opened domestic criminal proceedings to investigate potential war crimes in Ukraine.
