Europe’s plan to wean off Russian energy could lead to price shocks and political blowback
Return to menu
By Emily Rauhala and Rick Noack 7:07 p.m.
Link copied
Link

BRUSSELS — The invasion of Ukraine has convinced the European Union that it is time to wean off cheap and abundant Russian energy. But that won’t be easy — in fact, an E.U. official warned, it will be “bloody hard.”

A day after the European Commission presented a plan to cut Russian natural gas imports by two-thirds by year’s end, steeply reducing — but not outright banning — Russian energy, the E.U. nations are scrambling to figure out how to implement the measures and bracing for an economic punch that could shape politics for years to come.

Europe is broadly united in its desire to hit Russian President Vladimir Putin for his aggression and destruction in Ukraine. But across the continent, politicians are warning of price shocks and inflation. Energy prices risk becoming an issue in next month’s French presidential election. The word “embargo” was trending on German Twitter.
Read the full story ArrowRight
Bullet Key update
About 35,000 evacuated through humanitarian corridors, Zelensky says, as thousands more remain trapped
Return to menu
By Reis Thebault and David L. Stern 7:00 p.m.
Link copied
Link

Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelensky said late Wednesday that despite skepticism over Russia’s promised temporary cease-fires and scattered reports of continued shelling, about 35,000 people had been evacuated that day from conflict areas through three humanitarian corridors.

Ukrainian officials have said for days that Moscow is thwarting its civilian evacuation efforts : On Tuesday, one precarious route was available, from the city of Sumy in the country’s northeast. One day later, Zelensky said two more had opened, from the area around Kyiv and Enerhodar, a port city on the Dnieper River in southeastern Ukraine. Thousands remain trapped in several other cities under Russian assault. Leaders in Izyum said Russian forces were preventing their evacuation efforts.

“We will continue tomorrow,” Zelensky said in Wednesday’s video address. “We are preparing six corridors. We pray that people will be taken out of Mariupol, Izyum, Volnovakha, etc., taken to safe cities of our free Ukraine.”

Zelensky also denounced Russia’s reported bombing of a maternity hospital in Mariupol, accusing the Kremlin of indiscriminate killing.

“What kind of country is this, the Russian Federation, which is afraid of hospitals and maternity hospitals and destroys them?” Zelensky said, switching from Ukrainian to Russian, as if to make a direct appeal to a Russian audience.

“It is beyond atrocities already,” he said. “Everything that the invaders are doing to Mariupol is beyond atrocities already. Europeans! Ukrainians! Mariupol residents! Today, we must be united in condemning this war crime of Russia, which reflects all the evil that the invaders brought to our land.”
What are cluster and thermobaric ‘vacuum’ weapons, and how has Russia used them in the past?
Return to menu
By Claire Parker 6:30 p.m.
Link copied
Link

As more and more people are injured or killed in Russia’s war against Ukraine, Moscow faces mounting allegations that it has used cluster and vacuum weapons, which can put civilians at increased risk, particularly when used in urban areas.

International rights groups reported that cluster munitions apparently fired by Russia seemed to have hit a preschool in northeastern Ukraine and an area near a hospital in the Kyiv-controlled part of the eastern Donetsk region in late February, killing several civilians.

Russian forces, according to Ukraine and rights groups, also used cluster munitions in strikes on Kharkiv , the country’s second-largest city and the center of intense fighting between Ukrainian and Russian forces.

Britain’s Defense Ministry said Wednesday that its Russian counterpart had confirmed the deployment of the TOS-1A weapon system, which uses thermobaric rockets, in Ukraine.

Here’s what to know about those weapons.
